## 4. Defence Elements Checklist

{{ business_name }} may defend a statutory tort claim by establishing one or more of the following. Each defence requires supporting evidence.

### 4.1 Reasonable Steps Defence

Demonstrate that {{ business_name }} took reasonable steps to protect privacy:

- [ ] AI Privacy Policy in place and accessible to affected individuals
{% if has_privacy_policy %} *Status: {{ business_name }} has a privacy policy in place*
{% else %} **Gap: {{ business_name }} does not yet have a privacy policy — critical deficiency**
{% endif %}
- [ ] Privacy Impact Assessment conducted for AI systems processing personal information
{% if pia_conducted %} *Status: PIA has been conducted*
{% else %} **Gap: PIA has not been conducted — high priority remediation required**
{% endif %}
- [ ] AI Acceptable Use Policy distributed to all staff
- [ ] Staff trained on responsible AI use and privacy obligations
- [ ] Data minimisation applied — AI systems process only necessary personal information
- [ ] Retention limits enforced — AI interaction data deleted per retention schedule
- [ ] Access controls in place — only authorised personnel access AI systems and outputs
{% if essential_eight_applied %}- [ ] Essential Eight cyber security controls applied to AI infrastructure
{% else %}- [ ] **Gap: Essential Eight not yet applied — implement as a priority to strengthen defence**
{% endif %}

### 4.2 Legitimate Purpose Defence

Demonstrate that the AI processing served a legitimate purpose:

- [ ] Business justification documented for each AI system
- [ ] AI processing is necessary for the stated purpose (not merely convenient)
- [ ] Purpose limitation enforced — AI outputs are not repurposed beyond original intent
- [ ] Processing is proportionate to the purpose
{% for adt in automated_decision_types %}- [ ] Legitimate purpose documented for automated decision type: {{ adt }}
{% endfor %}

### 4.3 Consent Defence

Demonstrate that the individual consented to the AI processing:

- [ ] Consent mechanism records preserved (consent forms, click-through agreements, opt-in records)
- [ ] Consent was informed — individuals were told about AI processing specifically
{% if ai_disclosure_to_customers %}- [ ] AI disclosure to customers is in place — individuals know they are interacting with AI
{% else %}- [ ] **Gap: No AI disclosure to customers — consent may be undermined**
{% endif %}
- [ ] Consent was voluntary — not bundled with unrelated terms
- [ ] Consent withdrawal mechanism exists and is accessible
- [ ] Consent records are timestamped and tamper-evident

### 4.4 Public Interest Defence

Demonstrate that the AI processing was in the public interest:

- [ ] Public interest justification documented (e.g., fraud detection, safety, public health)
- [ ] Processing is proportionate to the public interest served
- [ ] Less privacy-invasive alternatives were considered and documented
- [ ] Public interest determination reviewed by {{ ai_governance_contact if ai_governance_contact else "the AI governance contact" }} or legal counsel

